# GIF Viewer Helper Predecode Notes

## Scope

This folder contains an experimental source build of the SourceForge GIF Viewer project with a Quivi-style helper predecode path.

Source project:

```text
https://sourceforge.net/projects/gifviewer/
https://git.code.sf.net/p/gifviewer/git
```

The installed system copy of GIF Viewer was not modified.

## Folder Layout

```text
gifviewer/
  source/              cloned source, with local experimental changes
  diffs/               change notes and hashes
  backups/             backups of edited source files
  tools/               smoke-test helper script
```

The moved `source/.git` metadata was removed to avoid shipping clone metadata or local paths.

## Current Experiment

The active experiment is in:

```text
source/GIFFile.cs
```

Behavior:

- `GifFile.LoadFromPath()` first checks for the Quivi/Pillow helper runtime next to the built executable.
- If present, GIF Viewer asks the helper to decode frames into temporary BMP files plus `delays.txt`.
- GIF Viewer loads those BMPs into 32bpp in-memory `Bitmap` frames.
- Playback then copies pixels from those predecoded frames.
- If the helper is missing or fails, GIF Viewer falls back to its original internal decoder.

Helper lookup order:

1. `webp_extract_pillow_runtime/webp_extract_pillow/webp_extract_pillow.exe`
2. `webp_extract_pillow.exe`

## Reverted Experiment

An earlier experiment forced nearest-neighbor scaling while playback was running.

That was reverted because it did not improve performance enough and made the quality selector appear ineffective during playback.

The note is kept for history:

```text
diffs/gifviewer-playback-fast-scaling.diff
```

The active helper experiment is documented here:

```text
diffs/gifviewer-helper-predecode.diff
```

## Build Command

The project targets .NET Framework 4.5 but was built locally with VS 2022 MSBuild/Roslyn using installed .NET Framework runtime assemblies:

```powershell
& "C:\Program Files\Microsoft Visual Studio\2022\Community\MSBuild\Current\Bin\MSBuild.exe" `
  "source\GIF Viewer.csproj" `
  /p:Configuration=Release `
  /p:Platform=AnyCPU `
  /p:FrameworkPathOverride="C:\Windows\Microsoft.NET\Framework\v4.0.30319" `
  /m
```

Expected output:

```text
source/bin/Release/GIF Viewer.exe
```

## Runtime Files

To exercise the helper path, place these beside the built executable:

```text
source/bin/Release/webp_extract_pillow_runtime/
source/bin/Release/webp_extract_pillow.exe
```

Those files were copied from the Quivi patched build during testing.

Without those helper files, the application should use its original decoder path.

## Smoke Test

Tool:

```text
tools/gifviewer_smoke_helper.ps1
```

The script expects a test GIF at:

```text
gifviewer/sample-512-80.gif
```

or:

```text
gifviewer/source/bin/Release/sample-512-80.gif
```

It launches the rebuilt viewer and checks whether the helper process appeared during loading.

Expected output includes:

```text
RUNNING=True
SAW_HELPER=True
```

## Tradeoffs

The helper path shifts work from playback time to load time.

Potential benefits:

- Less decoder work during playback.
- More predictable frame switching after load.
- Same helper runtime as the Quivi patch.

Costs:

- Higher initial load time.
- Higher RAM use, because full frames are materialized.
- Still experimental with large real-world GIFs.

## Public Release Hygiene

Before publishing or sharing:

- Keep `source/`, `diffs/`, `backups/`, and `tools/` if sharing development history.
- Exclude transient build folders if not needed.
- Do not include private test GIFs.
- Keep helper runtime files only if distributing a runnable experimental build.
- Review licenses for GIF Viewer and the helper runtime dependencies.

No private test paths or personal sample names should remain in the moved notes/scripts.
